      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0657P0-02342'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0657P0_20040114_GCR_307' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The noble Earl said: This is a paving amendment for Amendments Nos.102 to 104, to which my name is added. The group is designed to remove from the Bill the opportunity for both the Westminster Secretary of State, in Amendment No.102, and Scottish Ministers, in Amendment No.103, to make regulations that will create further circumstances under which disclosure is exempt from the criminal offence provisions.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0657P0-02343'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0657P0_20040114_GCR_308' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Subsection (4) is drafted to give a wide and broad-ranging list of the circumstances that will be exempt from the criminal offence provisions. It is difficult to conceive of circumstances in which either the Westminster Secretary of State or the Scottish Ministers would require to use regulations to expand
        
        <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_127gc' title='Col. 127GC &mdash; HL Deb 14 January 2004 vol 657 c127GC' name='column_127gc' href='#column_127gc' rel='bookmark'>127GC</a>
